[There have been 3 additional cases since the last ProMED-mail post bringing the total case count to 34. It is interesting to see the initial results of phylogenetic analysis becoming available so soon after the cases occurred. The minimal genotypic variation provides additional evidence of person to person transmission of the virus in this unusual outbreak. However, as noted previously, person to person transmission has happened before.

Mod.PMB provided a reference that indicates that in 1996, there was an outbreak of Andes virus Epilink/96 variant in El Bolson, Rio Negro province, and that, starting with the index case, a molecular analysis indicated that 15 cases occurred subsequently. Of these 16 patients, 9 died. Of the total cases, 8 probably became infected in a hospital environment, including 5 physicians (3 died) and a receptionist in a private clinic where 4 more cases occurred. The receptionist died. The data in this study suggest the possible existence of 3- and 4-person transmission chains, assuming that only one rodent-to-human transmission event occurred.

The progression of the current outbreak can be seen in the ProMED-mail posts listed below.

ProMED-mail thanks Dr. Palacios and colleagues for providing this early information. Results of phylogenetic analysis of the additional samples are awaited with interest. - Mod.TY

